# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Many patients with 6-phosphogluconate dehydrogenase deficiency are carriers and have no symptoms.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] It has been discovered that symptoms manifest more frequently in female carriers.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Depending on how severe the deficiency is, it has been demonstrated that enzyme activity is reduced by 35–65%.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] 6PGD deficiency is a recessive hereditary disorder located on the P arm of chromosome 1.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] It is an autosomal disease, not associated with the sex chromosomes and can affect both sexes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] The lack of synthesis of a specific protein on chromosome 1 has reduced a subject suffering from 6PGD deficiency from producing adequate amounts of the 6-phosphogluconate dehydrogenase enzyme.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Transfer of the disease can be passed from a parent, even when the parent is asymptomatic.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] 6-Phosphogluconate dehydrogenase (6PGD) is an enzyme in the pentose phosphate pathway (see image).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] 6PGD catalyzes the reaction of 6-phosphogluconate to an unstable form of 3-keto-6-phosphogluconate, and yields a co-enzyme nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate (NADPH) as a byproduct.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] The reaction is the second NADPH releasing reaction in the pentose phosphate pathway, the first being catalyzed by glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] 3-keto-6-phosphogluconate then rapidly (in an irreversible reaction) decarboxylates to CO2 and ribulose-5-phosphate, which is the precursor to many vital metabolic processes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] The NADPH pathway (both 6PGD and G6PD reactions) is the only source of reductant to reduce glutathione in red blood cells.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] The role of erythrocytes as oxygen carriers puts them at risk of being damaged by oxidizing free radicals.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] The reduction of glutathione acts as an antioxidant and prevents damage from reactive oxygen species.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] People suffering from 6PGD or G6PD deficiency (or both) are at risk of hemolytic anemia in states of oxidative stress.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Oxidative stress can result from infection and from chemical exposure to medication and certain foods.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Broad beans, e.g., fava beans, contain high levels of vicine, divicine, convicine and isouramil, all of which are oxidants.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] When all remaining reduced glutathione is consumed, enzymes and other proteins, such as hemoglobin are subsequently damaged by the free radicals, leading to electrolyte imbalance, cross-bonding and protein deposition in the red cell membranes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Damaged red cells are phagocytosed and sequestered (taken out of circulation) in the spleen.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] The hemoglobin is metabolized to bilirubin (causing jaundice).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] The red blood cells rarely disintegrate in the circulation, so hemoglobin is rarely excreted directly by the kidney, but this can occur in severe cases, causing acute kidney injury.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] The most important measure taken for treatment of 6-phosphoglucanate dehydrogenase is prevention.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Avoidance of chemical exposures to drugs and foods that have the potential to cause hemolysis.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Although some foods and supplements have antioxidant properties, their use does not decrease the severity of G6PD deficiency.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Diagnosis is difficult during haemolytic episodes since reticulocytes have increased levels of enzymes and may produce erroneously normal results.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Testing can be useful after a steady state is reached (about six weeks after the most recent episode of haemolysis), including a G6PD assay to confirm a diagnosis and G6PD spectrophotometry to detect the level of activity.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Vaccinations against some common pathogens (e.g. hepatitis A and hepatitis B) may prevent infection-induced attacks.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] In the acute phase of hemolysis, blood transfusions might be necessary, or even dialysis in acute kidney injury.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Blood transfusion is an important symptomatic measure, as the transfused red cells are generally not 6PGD deficient and will live a normal lifespan in the recipient's circulation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Causes of AKI are classified as either prerenal (due to decreased blood flow to the kidney), intrinsic renal (due to damage to the kidney itself), or postrenal (due to blockage of urine flow).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Prerenal causes of AKI include sepsis, dehydration, excessive blood loss, cardiogenic shock, heart failure, cirrhosis, and certain medications like ACE inhibitors or NSAIDs.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Intrinsic renal causes of AKI include glomerulonephritis, lupus nephritis, acute tubular necrosis, certain antibiotics, and chemotherapeutic agents.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Postrenal causes of AKI include kidney stones, bladder cancer, neurogenic bladder, enlargement of the prostate, narrowing of the urethra, and certain medications like anticholinergics.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] The diagnosis of AKI is made based on a person's signs and symptoms, along with lab tests measuring serum creatinine and urine output.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Other tests include urine microscopy and urine electrolytes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Renal ultrasound can be obtained when a postrenal cause is suspected.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] A kidney biopsy may be obtained when intrinsic renal AKI is suspected, and the cause is unclear.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] AKI is seen in 10–15% of people admitted to the hospital and in more than 50% of people admitted to the intensive care unit (ICU).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] AKI may lead to several complications, including metabolic acidosis, high potassium levels, uremia, changes in body fluid balance, effects on other organ systems, and death.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] People who have experienced AKI are at increased risk of developing chronic kidney disease in the future.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Management includes treatment of the underlying cause and supportive care, such as renal replacement therapy.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] The underlying cause often dominates the clinical presentation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] The symptoms of acute kidney injury result from various disturbances in kidney function that are associated with the disease.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Accumulation of urea and other nitrogen-containing substances in the bloodstream lead to a number of symptoms, such as fatigue, loss of appetite, headache, nausea, and vomiting.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Marked increases in the potassium level can lead to abnormal heart rhythms, which can be severe and life-threatening.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Fluid balance is frequently affected, though blood pressure can be high, low, or normal.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Pain in the flanks may be encountered in some conditions (such as clotting of the kidneys' blood vessels or inflammation of the kidney).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] This is the result of stretching of the fibrous tissue capsule surrounding the kidney.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] If the kidney injury is the result of dehydration, there may be thirst as well as evidence of fluid depletion on physical examination.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Physical examination may also provide other clues as to the underlying cause of the kidney problem, such as a rash in interstitial nephritis (or vasculitis) and a palpable bladder in obstructive nephropathy.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Intrinsic AKI refers to disease processes that directly damage the kidney itself.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Intrinsic AKI can be due to one or more of the kidney's structures, including the glomeruli, kidney tubules, or the interstitium.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Common causes of each are glomerulonephritis, acute tubular necrosis (ATN), and acute interstitial nephritis (AIN), respectively.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Other causes of intrinsic AKI are rhabdomyolysis and tumor lysis syndrome.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Certain medication classes such as antibiotics (e.g. amoxicillin/clavulanic acid) and calcineurin inhibitors (e.g., tacrolimus) can also directly damage the tubular cells of the kidney and result in a form of intrinsic AKI.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Introduced by the KDIGO in 2012, specific criteria exist for the diagnosis of AKI.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] The *RIFLE criteria*, proposed by the Acute Dialysis Quality Initiative (ADQI) group, aid in assessing the severity of a person's acute kidney injury.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] A measurable decrease in urine output may signal deterioration of kidney function.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Often, it is diagnosed based on blood tests for substances normally eliminated by the kidneys: urea and creatinine.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Additionally, the ratio of BUN to creatinine is used to evaluate kidney injury.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] For instance, it takes about 24 hours for the creatinine level to rise, even if both kidneys have ceased to function.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Several alternative markers have been proposed (such as NGAL, HAVCR1, IL18, and cystatin C), but none are sufficiently established as of 2018 to replace creatinine as a marker of kidney function.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] These may include urine sediment analysis, kidney ultrasound and/or kidney biopsy.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] AKI in the presence of the nephritic syndrome.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] In medical imaging, acute changes in the kidney are often examined with renal ultrasonography as the first-line modality, where CT scan and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) are used for follow-up examinations and when US fails to demonstrate abnormalities.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] In the evaluation of the acute changes in the kidney, the echogenicity of the renal structures, the delineation of the kidney, the renal vascularity, the kidney size, and focal abnormalities are observed.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] CT is preferred in renal traumas, but US is used for follow-up, especially in the patients suspected for the formation of urinomas.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] A CT scan of the abdomen will also demonstrate bladder distension or hydronephrosis.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Acute kidney injury is diagnosed based on clinical history and laboratory data.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] A diagnosis is made when there is a rapid reduction in kidney function, as measured by serum creatinine, or based on a rapid reduction in urine output, termed oliguria (less than 0.5 mL/kg/h for at least 6 hours).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] AKI can be caused by systemic disease, e.g., autoimmune conditions, like lupus nephritis), as well as other conditions, such as crush injury, contrast agents, some antibiotics, and more.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] The causes of acute kidney injury are commonly categorized into *prerenal*, *intrinsic*, and *postrenal*.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Acute kidney injury occurs in up to 30% of patients following cardiac surgery.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Mortality increases by 60-80% in post-cardiopulmonary bypass patients who go on to require renal replacement therapy.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Preoperative creatinine greater than 1.2 mg/dL, combined valve and bypass procedures, emergency surgery, and preoperative intra-aortic balloon pump are risk factors most strongly correlated with post-cardiopulmonary bypass acute kidney injury.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Other well-known minor risk factors include female gender, congestive heart failure, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, insulin-requiring diabetes, and depressed left ventricular ejection fraction.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Volatile anesthetic agents have been shown to increase renal sympathetic nerve activity (RSNA), which causes retention of salts and water, diminished renal blood flow (RBF) and an increase in serum renin levels, but not in antidiuretic hormone (ADH).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Postoperative acute kidney injury is defined as an AKI based on the KDIGO criteria occurring within 7 days of an operative intervention.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Pediatric AKI is defined using the KDIGO definition and the modified neonatal KDIGO criteria for neonates.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] The management of AKI hinges on identifying the underlying cause and treating it.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] The main objectives of initial management are to prevent cardiovascular collapse and death and to call for specialist advice from a nephrologist.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] In addition to treatment of the underlying disorder, management of AKI routinely includes the avoidance of substances that are toxic to the kidneys, called nephrotoxins.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] These include NSAIDs such as ibuprofen or naproxen, iodinated contrasts such as those used for CT scans, many antibiotics such as gentamicin, and a range of other substances.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Monitoring of kidney function, using serial serum creatinine measurements and monitoring of urine output, is routinely performed.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] In the hospital, insertion of a urinary catheter helps monitor urine output and relieve possible bladder outlet obstruction, such as with an enlarged prostate.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] In prerenal AKI without fluid overload, administration of intravenous fluids is typically the first step to improving kidney function.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Volume status may be monitored with the use of a central venous catheter to avoid over- or under-replacement of fluid.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] While a useful vasopressor, there is no evidence suggesting that dopamine is of any specific benefit and may in fact be harmful.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] The myriad causes of intrinsic AKI require specific therapies.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] For example, intrinsic AKI due to vasculitis or glomerulonephritis may respond to steroid medication, cyclophosphamide, and (in some cases) plasma exchange.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Toxin-induced prerenal AKI often responds to discontinuation of the offending agent, such as ACE inhibitors, ARB antagonists, aminoglycosides, penicillins, NSAIDs, or paracetamol.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] The use of diuretics such as furosemide is widespread and sometimes convenient in improving fluid overload.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] It is not associated with higher mortality (risk of death), nor with any reduced mortality or length of intensive care unit or hospital stay.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] If the cause is obstruction of the urinary tract, relief of the obstruction (with a nephrostomy or urinary catheter) may be necessary.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Renal replacement therapy, such as with hemodialysis, may be instituted in some cases of AKI.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Renal replacement therapy can be applied intermittently (IRRT) and continuously (CRRT).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Study results regarding differences in outcomes between IRRT and CRRT are inconsistent.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] A systematic review of the literature in 2008 demonstrated no difference in outcomes between the use of intermittent hemodialysis and continuous venovenous hemofiltration (CVVH) (a type of continuous hemodialysis).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Among critically ill patients, intensive renal replacement therapy with CVVH does not appear to improve outcomes compared to less intensive intermittent hemodialysis.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] However, other clinical and health economic studies demonstrated that, initiation of CRRT is associated with a lower likelihood of chronic dialysis and was cost-effective compared with IRRT in patients with acute kidney injury.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Metabolic acidosis, hyperkalemia, and pulmonary edema may require medical treatment with sodium bicarbonate, antihyperkalemic measures, and diuretics.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Lack of improvement with fluid resuscitation, therapy-resistant hyperkalemia, metabolic acidosis, or fluid overload may necessitate artificial support in the form of dialysis or hemofiltration.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] However, oliguria during anesthesia may predict AKI, but the effect of a fluid load is highly variable.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Striving toward a predefined urine output target to prevent AKI is futile.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] AKI recovery can be classified into three stages 1–3 based on the inverse of the AKI KDIGO serum creatinine criteria.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] AKI has a death rate as high as 20%, which may reach up to 50% in the intensive care unit (ICU).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Each year, around two million people die of AKI worldwide.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] AKI develops in 5% to 30% of patients who undergo cardiothoracic surgery, depending on the definition used for AKI.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] If AKI develops after major abdominal surgery (13.4% of all people who have undergone major abdominal surgery) the risk of death is markedly increased (over 12-fold).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Depending on the cause, a proportion of patients (5–10%) will never regain full kidney function, thus entering end-stage kidney failure and requiring lifelong dialysis or a kidney transplant.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Patients with AKI are more likely to die prematurely after being discharged from the hospital, even if their kidney function has recovered.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] The risk of developing chronic kidney disease is increased (8.8-fold).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] New cases of AKI are unusual but not rare, affecting approximately 0.1% of the UK population per year (2000 ppm/year), 20x incidence of new ESKD (end-stage kidney disease).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] AKI requiring dialysis (10% of these) is rare (200 ppm/year), 2x incidence of new ESKD.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Hot weather can increase the risk of AKI.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] For example, there is an increased incidence of AKI in agricultural workers because of occupational hazards such as dehydration and heat illness.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] No other traditional risk factors, including age, BMI, diabetes, or hypertension, were associated with incident AKI.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Acute kidney injury is common among hospitalized patients.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] It affects some 3–7% of patients admitted to the hospital and approximately 25–30% of patients in the intensive care unit.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Acute kidney injury was one of the most expensive conditions seen in U.S. hospitals in 2011, with an aggregated cost of nearly $4.7 billion for approximately 498,000 hospital stays.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] This was a 346% increase in hospitalizations from 1997, when there were 98,000 acute kidney injury stays.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] According to a review article of 2015, there has been an increase in cases of acute kidney injury in the last 20 years which cannot be explained solely by changes to the manner of reporting.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Clinical investigations have revealed a higher incidence of AKI and associated mortality in males compared to premenopausal women.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Before the advancement of modern medicine, acute kidney injury was referred to as *uremic poisoning* while uremia was contamination of the blood with urine.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Starting around 1847, *uremia* came to be used for reduced urine output, a condition now called oliguria, which was thought to be caused by the urine's mixing with the blood instead of being voided through the urethra.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] Acute kidney injury due to acute tubular necrosis (ATN) was recognized in the 1940s in the United Kingdom, where crush injury victims during the London Blitz developed patchy necrosis of kidney tubules, leading to a sudden decrease in kidney function.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/acute-kidney-injury] During the Korean and Vietnam wars, the incidence of AKI decreased due to better acute management and administration of intravenous fluids.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] A person inherits loss-of-function mutations in the *GBE1* gene from each parent, and the lack of glycogen branching enzyme (the protein encoded by *GBE1*) leads to the buildup of unbranched glycogen in cells, which harms neurons more than other kinds of cells.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] The condition is diagnosed by gathering symptoms, a neurological examination, laboratory tests including genetic testing, and medical imaging.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] As of 2025, there is no cure or treatment, but the symptoms can be managed.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] People diagnosed with APBD can live a long time after diagnosis, but will probably die earlier than people without the condition.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Adult polyglucosan body disease is a condition that affects the nervous system.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] People with this condition have problems walking due to reduced sensation in their legs (peripheral neuropathy) and progressive muscle weakness and stiffness (spasticity).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Damage to the nerves that control bladder function (neurogenic bladder) causes progressive difficulty in controlling the flow of urine.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] About half of people with adult polyglucosan body disease experience dementia.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Most people with the condition first complain of bladder issues.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] People with adult polyglucosan body disease typically first experience signs and symptoms related to the condition between ages 30 and 60.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] APBD is an autosomal recessive disorder that is caused when a person inherits genes from both parents containing one or more loss-of-function mutations in the gene *GBE1* which encodes for glycogen branching enzyme, also called 1,4-alpha-glucan-branching enzyme.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] According to reports, the most common disease-causing (pathogenic) variant of *GBE1* that is associated with APBD, particularly among those of Ashkenazi Jewish descent, is the p.Tyr329Ser (c.986A>C) mutation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] The *GBE1* gene provides instructions for making the glycogen branching enzyme.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] This enzyme is involved in the production of a complex sugar called glycogen, which is a major source of stored energy in the body.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Most *GBE1* gene mutations result in a shortage (deficiency) of the glycogen branching enzyme, which leads to the production of abnormal glycogen molecules. called polyglucosan.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Unlike normal glycogen, polyglucosan is made up of long, unbranched chains of glucose molecules.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] The lack of glycogen branching, which is controlled by the glycogen branching enzyme, makes the polyglucosan insoluble and difficult for the cell to metabolize.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] This results in the accumulation and aggregation of polyglucosan in the cell, forming polyglucosan bodies and causing cellular damage.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Neurons appear to be particularly vulnerable to the accumulation of polyglucosan bodies in people with this disorder, leading to impaired neuronal function.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Polyglucosan can accumulate in other organs of the body; in children with GSD IV, polyglucosan accumulation can damage the liver, skeletal muscles, and heart.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Some mutations in the *GBE1* gene that cause adult polyglucosan body disease do not result in a shortage of glycogen branching enzyme.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] In people with these mutations, the activity of this enzyme is normal.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] How mutations cause the disease in these individuals is unclear.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Other people with adult polyglucosan body disease do not have identified mutations in the *GBE1* gene.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] In these individuals, the cause of the disease is unknown.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Along with evaluation of the symptoms and a neurological examination, a diagnosis can be made based on genetic testing.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Whether or not a person is making sufficient amounts of functional glycogen branching enzyme can be determined by taking a skin biopsy and testing for activity of the enzyme.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Examination of tissue biopsied from the sural nerve under a microscope can reveal the presence of polyglucosan bodies.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] There will also be white matter changes visible in a magnetic resonance imaging scans.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Adult polyglucosan body disease is an orphan disease and a glycogen storage disorder that is caused by an inborn error of metabolism, that affects the central and peripheral nervous systems.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] The condition in newborns and children caused by the same mutations is called glycogen storage disease type IV (GSD IV).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] APBD can only be prevented if parents undergo genetic screening to understand their risk of producing a child with the condition; if in vitro fertilization is used, then preimplantation genetic diagnosis can be done to identify fertilized eggs that do not carry two copies of mutated *GBE1*.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] As of 2024, there is no cure for APBD; instead symptoms are managed.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] There are various approaches to managing neurogenic bladder dysfunction, physical therapy and mobility aids to help with walking, and dementia can be managed with occupational therapy, counseling and drugs.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] The rate of progression varies significantly from person to person.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] There is not good data on outcomes; it appears that APBD likely leads to earlier death, but people with APBD can live many years after diagnosis with relatively good quality of life.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] The exact prevalence of APBD is unknown.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] As of 2025, global prevalence estimates from the Rare Genomes Project suggest that there are approximately 34,000 people worldwide with *GBE1*-related diseases (APBD and GSD IV).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] In addition, APBD and *GBE1* mutations are most prevalent in individuals of Ashkenazi Jewish heritage (approximately 1/16,000).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] However, only about 160 cases of APBD had been reported in the medical literature as of 2020.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Historically, APBD and GSD IV have been classified as discrete diseases.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] However, detailed natural history and genome analysis studies have identified overlap in GBE1 gene mutations, as well as pathogenesis, between APBD and the GSD type IV variants.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Gregory Weiss, a person with APBD, created the Adult Polyglucosan Body Disease Research Foundation to fund research into the disease and its management.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] In 2015 the first transgenic mouse that appeared to be a useful model organism for studying APBD was published.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The low incidence of this syndrome is often related to aldolase A's essential glycolytic role along with its exclusive expression in blood and skeletal muscle.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Early developmental reliance and constitutive function prevents severe mutation in successful embryos.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Infrequent documentation thus prevents clear generalisation of symptoms and causes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] However five cases have been well described.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] ALDOA deficiency is diagnosed through reduced aldoA enzymatic activity, however, both physiological response and fundamental causes vary.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Blood-related pathology is seen in all patients.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Typically diagnosed at birth, congenital nonspherocytic hemolytic anemia is characterised by premature destruction of red blood cells without apparent abnormality in shape.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] This shortened erythrocyte life-span and increased destruction links to hyperbilirubinemia which often presents as jaundice in the accumulation of bilirubin through excessive hemoglobin breakdown.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Another side effect of cellular rupture both in the form of hemolysis and rabdomyolysis is excessive plasma concentrations of electrolytes such as potassium.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] This can lead to hyperkalemia, potentially of great cardiac concern.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Glycolysis also produces 2,3-diphosphoglycerate required to modulate hemoglobin's affinity for oxygen (2,3-bisphosphoglycerate synthesis).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Thus dysregulation of glycolysis is also implicated in the functional distribution of oxygen possibly leading to organ hypoxia.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] A complex pattern for this metabolite is suggested with discrepancy in findings.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] One Japanese patient had elevated levels, while the original Jewish Canadian boy had below average concentration.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Glucose metabolism also links intrinsically to the pentose phosphate pathway in the generation of reduced nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate (NADPH) necessary for synthetic processes and reduced glutathione involved in protecting red cells against oxidant damage.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] In particular increased fructose-1,6-bisphosphate accumulation can have inhibitory effects on glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase, an essential enzyme of this pathway.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Lactate accumulation has also been noted in some patients, potentially linked to reciprocal stimulation of pyruvate kinase, a key enzyme in lactic acid fermentation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] In non-contiguous patients an aggravated form of aldolase A deficiency has been seen to manifest in myopathy (muscular deterioration).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] This is often recognized initially through signs of muscle weakness and exercise intolerance, suggesting rapid muscular fatigue and damage, likely directly related to ATP depletion.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] This breakdown of muscular fibers, or rhabdomyolysis, can lead to detectable blood creatine phosphate level elevation and potentially exaggerated hyperkalemia.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Delayed growth and development was noted in some patients, although not fully explained, this may be generally associated with the physiological difficulties implicit in errors of energy metabolism.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] In particular neurological impairment was conjecturally linked with the predominant role of aldolase A in the brain during development.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] However, this was not substantiated with direct enzymatic kinetic study.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Elevated liver glycogen in one patent was rationalised through an accumulation of fructose-1,6-bisphosphate leading to impaired glucose metabolism and increased diversion of hexose sugars from peripheral tissues.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Within the liver the aldolase C isoform is unaffected and therefore hepatic metabolism is assumed to be normally functioning and compensatory processes may be operating.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Compromised immunity has also been indicated, relating to the predominance or exclusivity of aldolase A in leukocytes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] This was correlated with recurrent infection in the Sicilian case.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Focal disruption of vital energy metabolism has thus far prevented complete investigation of non-catalytic perturbation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] However relation to membrane structural stability has been implicated in the concurrence of aldolase A deficiency and dominant (mild) hereditary elliptocytosis, speculatively also relating to ATP depletion.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Characterised as a recessive disorder, symptomatic presentation requires the inheritance of aldolase A mutations from both parents.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] This conclusion is substantiated through the continuum type presentation witnessed, wherein heterozygous parents have intermediate enzyme activity.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Structural instability has been indicated in four of the patients, with particular sensitivity to increased temperature according to direct enzymatic testing.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] This is exemplified in the early diagnosis of hereditary pyropoikilocytosis in the Sicilian girl.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Deterioration with fever is likewise congruent.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] However, this direct relation has been disputed due to the increased overall metabolism and oxygen consumption also accompanying such maladies.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Sequence analysis has been conducted for three of the patients each revealing a distinct alteration at regions of typically high conservation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The conversion of the 128th aspartic acid to glycine causes conformational change according to CD spectral analysis and thermal lability in mutagenic analysis.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Similarly the charge disruption created through the exchange of the negatively charged glutamic acid for positively charged lysine (at residue 209 of the E helix) disrupts interface interaction of the protein's subunits and therein destabilises its native tetrahedral configuration.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The final case is unique in its non-homozygosity.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] A comparable maternal missense mutation wherein tyrosine is replaced by cysteine alters the carboxy-terminus due to its proximity to a crucial hinge structure.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] However, the paternal nonsense mutation at arginine 303 truncates the peptide.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] It is notable that Arg303 is required for enzymatic activity.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The initial 1973 case is atypical, in that no indication of aldolase A structural abnormality was found in isoelectric focusing, heat stabilization, electrophoresis or enzyme kinetics.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] It was concluded that either disordered regulation or a basic defect creating more rapid tetrameric inactivation were the most probable causes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The first recorded case of Aldolase A deficiency was described in 1973 (Beutler et al.) of a Jewish Canadian boy of Romanian descent.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] As his parents were first cousins, the presentation of dysmorphic features is conjecturally linked to confounding homozygosity at additional recessive loci.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Inborn errors of metabolism are not typically associated with malformation and subsequent cases have lacked such physical manifestations.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] In particular this leads to a complication for clearly delineating the effects of enzymatic aldolase-A deficiency.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The two familial male patients reported in 1981 (having been born in 1967 and 1979) were from a small Japanese island indicating a similar possibility of consanguinity.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] However, unlike in the primary instance parental aldolase activity was also partially reduced without significant physiological ailment.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The other two cases documented in 1996 and 2004 lacked evidence for contiguity and deviated from previous findings in demonstration of additional myopathic complaints.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The former boy's parents' and brother's aldolase activity's were half that of normal control values.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The Sicilian girl's mother had benign hereditary elliptocytosis, a dominant condition resulting in elongated erythrocytes, which was passed on to her.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] However, her father's blood count and smear produced normal findings.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFold 1 (2018) placed first in the overall rankings of the 13th Critical Assessment of Structure Prediction (CASP) in December 2018.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] It was particularly successful at predicting the most accurate structures for targets rated as most difficult by the competition organizers, where no existing template structures were available from proteins with partially similar sequences.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFold 2 (2020) repeated this placement in the CASP14 competition in November 2020.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] It achieved a level of accuracy much higher than any other entry.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] It scored above 90 on CASP's global distance test (GDT) for approximately two-thirds of the proteins, a test measuring the similarity between a computationally predicted structure and the experimentally determined structure, where 100 represents a complete match.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The inclusion of metagenomic data has improved the quality of the prediction of multiple sequence alignments.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] One of the biggest sources of the training data was the custom-built Big Fantastic Database of 65,983,866 protein families, represented as multiple sequence alignments and Hidden Markov models, covering 2,204,359,010 protein sequences from reference databases, metagenomes, and metatranscriptomes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFold 2's results at CASP14 were described as "astounding" and "transformational".
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] However, some researchers noted that the accuracy was insufficient for a third of its predictions, and that it did not reveal the underlying mechanism or rules of protein folding for the protein folding problem, which remains unsolved.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Despite this, the technical achievement was widely recognized.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] On 15 July 2021, the AlphaFold 2 paper was published in *Nature* as an advance access publication alongside open source software and a searchable database of species proteomes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] As of November 2025, the paper had been cited nearly 43,000 times.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFold 3 was announced on 8 May 2024.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] It can predict the structure of complexes created by proteins with DNA, RNA, various ligands, and ions.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The new prediction method shows a minimum 50% improvement in accuracy for protein interactions with other molecules compared to existing methods.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Proteins consist of chains of amino acids which spontaneously fold to form the three dimensional (3-D) structures of the proteins.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The 3-D structure is necessary to understanding the biological function of the protein.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Protein structures can be determined experimentally through techniques such as X-ray crystallography, cryo-electron microscopy and nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), which are all expensive and time-consuming.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Such efforts, using the experimental methods, have identified the structures of about 170,000 proteins over the last 60 years, while there are over 200 million known proteins across all life forms.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Over the years, researchers have applied numerous computational methods to predict the 3D structures of proteins from their amino acid sequences, accuracy of such methods in best possible scenario is close to experimental techniques (NMR) by the use of homology modeling based on molecular evolution.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] CASP, which was launched in 1994 to challenge the scientific community to produce their best protein structure predictions, found that GDT scores of only about 40 out of 100 can be achieved for the most difficult proteins by 2016.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFold started competing in the 2018 CASP using an artificial intelligence (AI) deep learning technique.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] DeepMind is known to have trained the program on over 170,000 protein structures from the Protein Data Bank, a public repository of protein sequences and structures.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The program uses a form of attention network, a deep learning technique that focuses on having the AI identify parts of a larger problem, then piece it together to obtain the overall solution.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The overall training was conducted on processing power between 100 and 200 GPUs.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The 2020 version of the program (**AlphaFold 2**, 2020) is significantly different from the original version that won CASP 13 in 2018, according to the team at DeepMind.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFold 1 used a number of separately trained modules to produce a guide potential, which was then combined with a physics-based energy potential.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFold 2 replaced this with a system of interconnected sub-networks, forming a single, differentiable, end-to-end model based on pattern recognition.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] This model was trained in an integrated manner.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] After the neural network's prediction converges, a final refinement step applies local physical constraints using energy minimization based on the AMBER force field.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] This step only slightly adjusts the predicted structure.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Internally these refinement transformations contain layers that have the effect of bringing relevant data together and filtering out irrelevant data (the "attention mechanism") for these relationships, in a context-dependent way, learned from training data.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The output of these iterations then informs the final structure prediction module, which also uses transformers, and is itself then iterated.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] In an example presented by DeepMind, the structure prediction module achieved a correct topology for the target protein on its first iteration, scored as having a GDT_TS of 78, but with a large number (90%) of stereochemical violations – i.e. unphysical bond angles or lengths.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] With subsequent iterations the number of stereochemical violations fell.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] By the third iteration the GDT_TS of the prediction was approaching 90, and by the eighth iteration the number of stereochemical violations was approaching zero.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The training data was originally restricted to single peptide chains.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] However, the October 2021 update, named AlphaFold-Multimer, included protein complexes in its training data.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] DeepMind stated this update succeeded about 70% of the time at accurately predicting protein-protein interactions.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Announced on 8 May 2024, **AlphaFold 3** was co-developed by Google DeepMind and Isomorphic Labs, both subsidiaries of Alphabet.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFold 3 is not limited to proteins, as it can also predict the structures of protein complexes with DNA, RNA, post-translational modifications and selected ligands and ions.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFold 3 introduces the "Pairformer," a deep learning architecture inspired by the transformer, which is considered similar to, but simpler than, the Evoformer used in AlphaFold 2.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The Pairformer module's initial predictions are refined by a diffusion model.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] This model begins with a cloud of atoms and iteratively refines their positions, guided by the Pairformer's output, to generate a 3D representation of the molecular structure.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The AlphaFold server was created to provide free access to AlphaFold 3 for non-commercial research.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] As of November 2025, the AlphaFold 3 research paper has been directly cited more than 9,000 times.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] In December 2018, DeepMind's AlphaFold placed first in the overall rankings of the 13th Critical Assessment of Techniques for Protein Structure Prediction (CASP).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The program was particularly successfully predicting the most accurate structure for targets rated as the most difficult by the competition organisers, where no existing template structures were available from proteins with a partially similar sequence.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFold gave the best prediction for 25 out of 43 protein targets in this class, achieving a median score of 58.9 on the CASP's global distance test (GDT) score, ahead of 52.5 and 52.4 by the two next best-placed teams, who were also using deep learning to estimate contact distances.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Overall, across all targets, AlphaFold 1 achieved a GDT score of 68.5.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] In January 2020, implementations and illustrative code of AlphaFold 1 was released open-source on GitHub. but, as stated in the "Read Me" file on that website: "This code can't be used to predict structure of an arbitrary protein sequence.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] It can be used to predict structure only on the CASP13 dataset (links below).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The feature generation code is tightly coupled to our internal infrastructure as well as external tools, hence we are unable to open-source it." Therefore, in essence, the code deposited is not suitable for general use but only for the CASP13 proteins.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The company has not announced plans to make their code publicly available as of 5 March 2021.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] In November 2020, DeepMind's new version, AlphaFold 2, won CASP14.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Overall, AlphaFold 2 made the best prediction for 88 out of the 97 targets.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] In 2018 AlphaFold 1 had only reached this level of accuracy in two of all of its predictions.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] 88% of predictions in the 2020 competition had a GDT_TS score of more than 80.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] On the group of targets classed as the most difficult, AlphaFold 2 achieved a median score of 87.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] 76% of predictions achieved better than 3 Å, and 46% had a C-alpha atom RMS accuracy better than 2 Å, with a median RMS deviation in its predictions of 2.1 Å for a set of overlapped CA atoms.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFold 2 also achieved an accuracy in modelling surface side chains described as "really really extraordinary".
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] To further validate AlphaFold 2, the conference organizers approached four leading experimental groups working on structures they found particularly challenging and had been unable to determine.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] In all four cases the three-dimensional models produced by AlphaFold 2 were sufficiently accurate to determine structures of these proteins by molecular replacement.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] These included target T1100 (Af1503), a small membrane protein studied by experimentalists for ten years.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Of the three structures that AlphaFold 2 had the least success in predicting, one was an unusual multidomain complex consisting of 52 identical copies of the same domain.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] For all targets with a single domain, excluding only one very large protein and the two structures determined by NMR, AlphaFold 2 achieved a GDT_TS score of over 80.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] In 2022, DeepMind did not enter CASP15, but most of the entrants used AlphaFold or tools incorporating AlphaFold.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFold 2 scoring more than 90 in CASP's global distance test (GDT) is a great achievement in computational biology.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Nobel Prize winner and structural biologist Venki Ramakrishnan called the result "a stunning advance on the protein folding problem", adding that "It has occurred decades before many people in the field would have predicted.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFold 2's success received wide media attention.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] News pieces appeared in the science press, such as *Nature*, *Science*, *MIT Technology Review*, and *New Scientist*, and the story was covered by national newspapers.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] A frequent theme was the ability to predict protein structures based on the constituent amino acid sequence, expected to have benefits in the life sciences—accelerating drug discovery and enabling better understanding of diseases.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Some have noted that even a perfect answer to the protein *prediction* problem still leaves questions about the protein *folding* problem (and thus protein dynamics)—understanding in detail how the folding process actually occurs in nature (and how sometimes they can also misfold).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] In 2023, Demis Hassabis and John Jumper won the Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences as well as the Albert Lasker Award for Basic Medical Research for their management of the AlphaFold project.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Hassabis and Jumper proceeded to win the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 2024 for their work on "protein structure prediction" with David Baker of the University of Washington.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Open access to source code of several AlphaFold versions (excluding AlphaFold 3) has been provided by DeepMind in 2022 after requests from the scientific community.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The source code and weights of AlphaFold 3 were made available for non-commercial use to the scientific community upon request in November 2024.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] It became publicly available in February 2025, still retaining the non-commercial restriction.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] A number of AlphaFold clones have also been published, mostly with permissive license terms.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Clones for AlphaFold3 include ByteDance's Protenix (Apache 2.0 License), AlQuraishi Laboratory's OpenFold-3 (MIT license), and Boltz-1/2 (MIT license).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] There are also clones for older versions, though they became less relevant with the open-source release of AlphaFold 1 and 2 source codes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Still relevant are models, both open- and closed-source, that include modifications to the AlphaFold architecture.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] For AlphaFold 2, a notable example is ESMFold from Meta, which replaces the multiple sequence alignment with the latent space of a protein language model.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Open-source tools that complement AlphaFold have also been made.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] One well-cited example is ColabFold, which uses MMseqs2 instead of HHblits to speed up the sequence search, allowing the AlphaFold pipelines to run quickly on Google Colab.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The **AlphaFold Protein Structure Database** (AFDB), a joint project between AlphaFold and EMBL-EBI, was launched on July 22, 2021.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] At launch, the database contained AlphaFold 1-predicted models for nearly the complete UniProt proteome of humans and 20 model organisms, totaling over 365,000 proteins.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The database does not include proteins with fewer than 16 or more than 2700 amino acid residues, but for humans they are available in the whole batch file.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFold's initial goal (as of early 2022) was to expand the database to cover most of the UniRef90 set, which contains over 100 million proteins.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] As of May 15, 2022, the database contained 992,316 predictions.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] In July 2021, UniProt-KB and InterPro has been updated to show AlphaFold predictions when available.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] On July 28, 2022, the team uploaded to the database the structures of around 200 million proteins from 1 million species, covering nearly every known protein on the planet.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The number as of 2024 is 214 million, with 26 million being duplicates (exact sequence matches) of another protein in the database.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The predicted structures can differ significantly between duplicates.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] As of 2025, the AFDB uses AlphaFold 2 for its predictions.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] All structures produced remain monomeric, but multimeric structures produced by other databases are linked on the page through the 3D-Beacons API.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Foldseek, which provides fast and accurate structure searches, is also integrated.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Information from AlphaMissense (a tool that uses AlphaFold to predict the outcome of missense mutations) is also integrated.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFill adds cofactors to AlphaFold models where appropriate.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] This is achieved by searching the Protein Data Bank for similar structures and transplanting cofactors to analogous positions.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] TmAlphaFold docks AlphaFold models to biological membranes, similar to what OPM does for PDB structures.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AFTM uses AlphaFold models to identify transmembrane regions in human proteins, similar to what PDBTM does for PDB structures.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] ChannelsDB 2.0 uses PDB or AlphaFill models to calculate the pathway a molecule may take to reach an enzyme's active site or to reach another side of a transmembrane pore.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The AFDB is not updated with UniProt sequences changes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaSync keeps the AFDB in sync with UniProt entry changes, generating updated structures, residue-level features and contacts.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] It tries to use an AFDB entry for the exact updated sequence when available and run AlphaFold 2 independently otherwise.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] It fills in AFDB's blank for large (> 2,700 aa) proteins and proteins with special FASTA characters such as B, Z, U or X.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The Encyclopedia of Domains (TED) applies the domain-recognition method from CATH database to 188 million unique structures from the AFDB, identifying nearly 365 million domains, which is 100 million more than what sequence-based methods could identify.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The Evolutionary Classification of Protein Domains database (ECOD) assigns ECOD classifications to all SwissProt proteins in AFDB.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] isoform.io is a database of AlphaFold2-generated structures of proposed splice isoforms in the human genome.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] It includes information from 237,275 human transcripts.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] It has been used to detect errors in the mRNA predictions for a handful of genes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFold has shown certain limitations.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] AlphaFold has been used to predict structures of proteins of SARS-CoV-2, the causative agent of COVID-19.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The structures of these proteins were pending experimental detection in early 2020.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Results were reviewed by scientists at the Francis Crick Institute in the United Kingdom before being released to the broader research community.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The team also confirmed accurate prediction against the experimentally determined SARS-CoV-2 spike protein that was shared in the Protein Data Bank, an international open-access database, before releasing the computationally determined structures of the under-studied protein molecules.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] The team acknowledged that although these protein structures might not be the subject of ongoing therapeutical research efforts, they will add to the community's understanding of the SARS-CoV-2 virus.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] Specifically, AlphaFold 2's prediction of the structure of the *ORF3a* protein was very similar to the structure determined by researchers at University of California, Berkeley using cryo-electron microscopy.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] This specific protein is believed to assist the virus in breaking out of the host cell once it replicates.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/alphafold] This protein is also believed to play a role in triggering the inflammatory response to the infection.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It should not be confused with cyclic AMP-activated protein kinase (protein kinase A).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK is a heterotrimeric protein complex that is formed by α, β, and γ subunits.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Each of these three subunits takes on a specific role in both the stability and activity of AMPK.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Specifically, the γ subunit includes four particular Cystathionine-β-synthase (CBS) domains, giving AMPK its ability to sensitively detect shifts in the AMP/ATP ratio.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK is deactivated upon AMP displacement by ATP at CBS site 3, suggesting CBS3 to be the primary allosteric regulatory site.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The four CBS domains create two binding sites for AMP commonly referred to as Bateman domains.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Binding of one AMP to a Bateman domain cooperatively increases the binding affinity of the second AMP to the other Bateman domain.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] As AMP binds both Bateman domains the γ subunit undergoes a conformational change which exposes the catalytic domain found on the α subunit.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It is in this catalytic domain where AMPK becomes activated when phosphorylation takes place at threonine-172 (on α1 isoform) or Thr-174 (on α2 isoform) by an upstream AMPK kinase (AMPKK).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The α, β, and γ subunits can also be found in different isoforms: the γ subunit can exist as either the γ1, γ2 or γ3 isoform; the β subunit can exist as either the β1 or β2 isoform; and the α subunit can exist as either the α1 or α2 isoform.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Although the most common isoforms expressed in most cells are the α1, β1, and γ1 isoforms, it has been demonstrated that the α2, β2, γ2, and γ3 isoforms are also expressed in cardiac and skeletal muscle.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The crystal structure of mammalian AMPK regulatory core domain (α C terminal, β C terminal, γ) has been solved in complex with AMP, ADP or ATP.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Due to the presence of isoforms of its components, there are 12 versions of AMPK in mammals, each of which can have different tissue localizations, and different functions under different conditions.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK is regulated allosterically and by post-translational modification, which work together.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] If residue Thr-172 of AMPK's α1-subunit (or Thr-174 of AMPK's α2-subunit) is phosphorylated, AMPK is activated around 100-fold; access to that residue by phosphatases is blocked if AMP or ADP can block access for and ATP can displace AMP and ADP.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Regulation of AMPK by CaMKK2 requires a direct interaction of these two proteins via their kinase domains.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The interaction of CaMKK2 with AMPK only involves the α and β subunits of AMPK (AMPK γ is absent from the CaMKK2 complex), thus rendering regulation of AMPK in this context to changes in calcium levels but not AMP or ADP.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK is regulated allosterically mostly by competitive binding to the CBS sites on its γ subunit between ATP (which allows phosphatase access to Thr-172) and AMP or ADP (each of which blocks access to phosphatases).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It thus appears that AMPK is a sensor of AMP/ATP or ADP/ATP ratios and thus cell energy level.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK undergoes a large conformational change upon ATP binding.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] A region on the α subunit known as the kinase domain (KD) dissociates from its active-state conformation and loosely associates with the γ subunit ~100Å away.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The KD also rotates ~180° in the conformational change.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Upon KD dissociation, the active loop (AL) of the α subunit which contains the critical phosphorylated Thr residue is fully exposed to upstream phosphatases.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] This conformational change represents a plausible mechanism for AMPK modulation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] When cellular energy states are low (high AMP/ATP or ADP/ATP levels), AMPK adopts the KD-associated conformation and AMPK is protected from dephosphorylation and remains activated.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] When cellular energy states are high, AMPK adopts the KD-displaced conformation, the AL is exposed to upstream phosphatases, and AMPK is deactivated.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The pharmacological compounds Merck Compound 991 and Abbott A769662 bind to the allosteric drug and metabolism site (ADaM) on the β subunit and have been shown to activate AMPK up to 10-fold.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] ADaM site binding may have roles in AMPK activation as well as protection against dephosphorylation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] There are other mechanisms by which AMPK is inhibited or activated by insulin, leptin, and diacylglycerol by inducing various other phosphorylations.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK may be inhibited or activated by various tissue-specific ubiquitinations.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It is also regulated by several protein-protein interactions, and may either be activated or inhibited by oxidative factors; the role of oxidation in regulating AMPK was controversial as of 2016.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] When AMPK phosphorylates acetyl-CoA carboxylase 1 (ACC1) or sterol regulatory element-binding protein 1c (SREBP1c), it inhibits synthesis of fatty acids, cholesterol, and triglycerides, and activates fatty acid uptake and β-oxidation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK stimulates glucose uptake in skeletal muscle by phosphorylating Rab-GTPase-activating protein TBC1D1, which ultimately induces fusion of GLUT4 vesicles with the plasma membrane.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK stimulates glycolysis by activating phosphorylation of 6-phosphofructo-2-kinase/fructose-2,6-bisphosphatase 2/3 and activating phosphorylation of glycogen phosphorylase, and it inhibits glycogen synthesis through inhibitory phosphorylation of glycogen synthase.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] In the liver, AMPK inhibits gluconeogenesis by inhibiting transcription factors including hepatocyte nuclear factor 4 (HNF4) and CREB regulated transcription coactivator 2 (CRTC2).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK inhibits the energy-intensive protein biosynthesis process and can also force a switch from cap-dependent translation to cap-independent translation, which requires less energy, by phosphorylation of TSC2, RPTOR, transcription initiation factor 1A.66, and eEF2K.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] When TSC2 is activated it inhibits mTORC1.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] As a result of inhibition of mTORC1 by AMPK, protein synthesis comes to a halt.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Activation of AMPK signifies low energy within the cell, so all of the energy consuming pathways like protein synthesis are inhibited, and pathways that generate energy are activated to restore appropriate energy levels in the cell.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK activates autophagy by directly and indirectly activating ULK1.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK also appears to stimulate mitochondrial biogenesis by regulating PGC-1α which in turn promotes gene transcription in mitochondria.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK also activates anti-oxidant defenses.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Additionally, recent discoveries can conceivably suggest a direct AMPK role in increasing blood supply to exercised/trained muscle cells by stimulating and stabilizing both vasculogenesis and angiogenesis.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Taken together, these adaptations most likely transpire as a result of both temporary and maintained increases in AMPK activity brought about by increases in the AMP:ATP ratio during single bouts of exercise and long-term training.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] During a single acute exercise bout, AMPK allows the contracting muscle cells to adapt to the energy challenges by increasing expression of hexokinase II, translocation of GLUT4 to the plasma membrane, for glucose uptake, and by stimulating glycolysis.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] If bouts of exercise continue through a long-term training regimen, AMPK and other signals will facilitate contracting muscle adaptations by escorting muscle cell activity to a metabolic transition resulting in a fatty-acid oxidation approach to ATP generation as opposed to a glycolytic approach.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK accomplishes this transition to the oxidative mode of metabolism by upregulating and activating oxidative enzymes such as hexokinase II, PPAR-α, PPAR-δ, PGC-1, UCP-3, cytochrome C and TFAM.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Mutations in the skeletal muscle calcium release channel (RYR1) underlies a life- threatening response to heat in patients with malignant hyperthermia susceptibility (MHS).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Upon acute exposure to heat, these mutations cause uncontrolled Ca2+ release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum, leading to sustained muscle contractures, severe hyperthermia, and sudden death.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] At basal conditions, the temperature-dependent Ca2+ leak also leads to increased energy demand and activation of energy sensing AMP kinase (AMPK) in skeletal muscle.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The activated AMPK increases muscle metabolic activity, including glycolysis, which leads to marked elevation of circulating lactate.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK activity increases with exercise and the LKB1/MO25/STRAD complex is considered to be the major upstream AMPKK of the 5’-AMP-activated protein kinase phosphorylating the α subunit of AMPK at Thr-172.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] This fact is puzzling considering that although AMPK protein abundance has been shown to increase in skeletal tissue with endurance training, its level of activity has been shown to decrease with endurance training in both trained and untrained tissue.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Currently, the activity of AMPK immediately following a 2 hour bout of exercise of an endurance trained rat is unclear.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It is possible that a direct link exists between the observed decrease in AMPK activity in endurance trained skeletal muscle and the apparent decrease in the AMPK response to exercise with endurance training.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Although AMPKα2 activation has been thought to be important for mitochondrial adaptations to exercise training, a recent study investigating the response to exercise training in AMPKα2 knockout mice opposes this idea.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Their study compared the response to exercise training of several proteins and enzymes in wild type and AMPKα2 knockout mice.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] And even though the knockout mice had lower basal markers of mitochondrial density (COX-1, CS, and HAD), these markers increased similarly to the wild type mice after exercise training.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] These findings are supported by another study also showing no difference in mitochondrial adaptations to exercise training between wild type and knockout mice.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The *C. elegans* homologue of AMPK, aak-2, has been shown by Michael Ristow and colleagues to be required for extension of life span in states of glucose restriction mediating a process named mitohormesis.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] One of the effects of exercise is an increase in fatty acid metabolism, which provides more energy for the cell.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] One of the key pathways in AMPK's regulation of fatty acid oxidation is the phosphorylation and inactivation of acetyl-CoA carboxylase.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Acetyl-CoA carboxylase (ACC) converts acetyl-CoA to malonyl-CoA, an inhibitor of carnitine palmitoyltransferase 1 (CPT-1).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] CPT-1 transports fatty acids into the mitochondria for oxidation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Inactivation of ACC, therefore, results in increased fatty acid transport and subsequent oxidation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It is also thought that the decrease in malonyl-CoA occurs as a result of malonyl-CoA decarboxylase (MCD), which may be regulated by AMPK.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] MCD is an antagonist to ACC, decarboxylating malonyl-CoA to acetyl-CoA, resulting in decreased malonyl-CoA and increased CPT-1 and fatty acid oxidation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK also plays an important role in lipid metabolism in the liver.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It has long been known that hepatic ACC has been regulated in the liver by phosphorylation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK also phosphorylates and inactivates 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA reductase (HMGCR), a key enzyme in cholesterol synthesis.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] HMGR converts 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA, which is made from acetyl-CoA, into mevalonic acid, which then travels down several more metabolic steps to become cholesterol.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK, therefore, helps regulate fatty acid oxidation and cholesterol synthesis.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Insulin is a hormone which helps regulate glucose levels in the body.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] When blood glucose is high, insulin is released from the Islets of Langerhans.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Insulin, among other things, will then facilitate the uptake of glucose into cells via increased expression and translocation of glucose transporter GLUT-4.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Under conditions of exercise, however, blood sugar levels are not necessarily high, and insulin is not necessarily activated, yet muscles are still able to bring in glucose.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK seems to be responsible in part for this exercise-induced glucose uptake.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Goodyear et al. observed that with exercise, the concentration of GLUT-4 was increased in the plasma membrane, but decreased in the microsomal membranes, suggesting that exercise facilitates the translocation of vesicular GLUT-4 to the plasma membrane.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] While acute exercise increases GLUT-4 translocation, endurance training will increase the total amount of GLUT-4 protein available.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It has been shown that both electrical contraction and AICA ribonucleotide (AICAR) treatment increase AMPK activation, glucose uptake, and GLUT-4 translocation in perfused rat hindlimb muscle, linking exercise-induced glucose uptake to AMPK.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Chronic AICAR injections, simulating some of the effects of endurance training, also increase the total amount of GLUT-4 protein in the muscle cell.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Two proteins are essential for the regulation of GLUT-4 expression at a transcriptional level – myocyte enhancer factor 2 (MEF2) and GLUT4 enhancer factor (GEF).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Mutations in the DNA binding regions for either of these proteins results in ablation of transgene GLUT-4 expression.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] These results prompted a study in 2005 which showed that AMPK directly phosphorylates GEF, but it doesn't seem to directly activate MEF2.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AICAR treatment has been shown, however, to increase transport of both proteins into the nucleus, as well as increase the binding of both to the GLUT-4 promoter region.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] There is another protein involved in carbohydrate metabolism that is worthy of mention along with GLUT-4.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The enzyme hexokinase phosphorylates a six-carbon sugar, most notably glucose, which is the first step in glycolysis.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] When glucose is transported into the cell it is phosphorylated by hexokinase.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] This phosphorylation keeps glucose from leaving the cell, and by changing the structure of glucose through phosphorylation, it decreases the concentration of glucose molecules, maintaining a gradient for more glucose to be transported into the cell.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Hexokinase II transcription is increased in both red and white skeletal muscle upon treatment with AICAR.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] With chronic injections of AICAR, total protein content of hexokinase II increases in rat skeletal muscle.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Mitochondrial enzymes, such as cytochrome c, succinate dehydrogenase, malate dehydrogenase, α-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase, and citrate synthase, increase in expression and activity in response to exercise.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AICAR stimulation of AMPK increases cytochrome c and δ-aminolevulinate synthase (ALAS), a rate-limiting enzyme involved in the production of heme.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Malate dehydrogenase and succinate dehydrogenase also increase, as well as citrate synthase activity, in rats treated with AICAR injections.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Conversely, in LKB1 knockout mice, there are decreases in cytochrome c and citrate synthase activity, even if the mice are "trained" by voluntary exercise.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK is required for increased peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor γ coactivator-1α (PGC-1α) expression in skeletal muscle in response to creatine depletion.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] PGC-1α is a transcriptional regulator for genes involved in fatty acid oxidation, gluconeogenesis, and is considered the master regulator for mitochondrial biogenesis.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] To do this, it enhances the activity of transcription factors like nuclear respiratory factor 1 (NRF-1), myocyte enhancer factor 2 (MEF2), host cell factor (HCF), and others.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It also has a positive feedback loop, enhancing its own expression.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Both MEF2 and cAMP response element (CRE) are essential for contraction-induced PGC-1α promoter activity.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] LKB1 knockout mice show a decrease in PGC-1α, as well as mitochondrial proteins.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK and thyroid hormone regulate some similar processes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Knowing these similarities, Winder and Hardie et al. designed an experiment to see if AMPK was influenced by thyroid hormone.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] They found that all of the subunits of AMPK were increased in skeletal muscle, especially in the soleus and red quadriceps, with thyroid hormone treatment.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] There was also an increase in phospho-ACC, a marker of AMPK activity.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Loss of AMPK has been reported to alter the sensitivity of glucose sensing cells, through poorly defined mechanisms.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Loss of the AMPKα2 subunit in pancreatic β-cells and hypothalamic neurons decreases the sensitivity of these cells to changes in extracellular glucose concentration.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Moreover, exposure of rats to recurrent bouts of insulin induced hypoglycemia/glucopenia, reduces the activation of AMPK within the hypothalamus, whilst also suppressing the counterregulatory response to hypoglycemia.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Pharmacological activation of AMPK by delivery of AMPK activating drug AICAR, directly into the hypothalamus can increase the counterregulatory response to hypoglycaemia.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK is recruited to lysosomes and regulated at the lysosomes via several systems of clinical significance.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Both of the above lysosomally localized systems controlling AMPK activate it in response to metformin, a widely prescribed anti-diabetic drug.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Some evidence indicates that AMPK may have a role in tumor suppression.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Studies have found that AMPK may exert most, or even all of, the tumor suppressing properties of liver kinase B1 (LKB1).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Additionally, studies where the AMPK activator metformin was used to treat diabetes found a correlation with a reduced risk of cancer, compared to other medications.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] In contrast, some studies have linked AMPK with a role as a tumor promoter by protecting cancer cells from stress.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Thus, once cancerous cells have formed in an organism, AMPK may swap from protecting against cancer to protecting the cancer itself.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Studies have found that tumor cells with AMPK knockout are more susceptible to death by glucose starvation or extracellular matrix detachment, which may indicate AMPK has a role in preventing these two outcomes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] A recent study on pancreatic cancer suggests that AMPKα may play a role in the metastatic cascade and the phenotype of cancer cells.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Mechanistically, the authors propose that in the absence of AMPKα, pancreatic cancer cells are more vulnerable to oxidative stress, supporting a tumor-promoting function of AMPKα.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] A seemingly paradoxical role of AMPK occurs when we take a closer look at the energy-sensing enzyme in relation to exercise and long-term training.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Conversely, the study did not observe the same results in white quadriceps (WQ) and soleus (SOL) muscles that they did in RQ.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The trained rats used for that endurance study ran on treadmills 5 days/wk in two 1-h sessions, morning and afternoon.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The rats were also running up to 31m/min (grade 15%).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Finally, following training, the rats were sacrificed either at rest or following 10 minutes of exercise.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Because the AMPK response to exercise decreases with increased training duration, many questions arise that would challenge the AMPK role with respect to biochemical adaptations to exercise and endurance training.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] This is due in part to the marked increases in the mitochondrial biogenesis, upregulation of GLUT-4, UCP-3, Hexokinase II along with other metabolic and mitochondrial enzymes despite decreases in AMPK activity with training.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Questions also arise because skeletal muscle cells which express these decreases in AMPK activity in response to endurance training also seem to be maintaining an oxidative dependent approach to metabolism, which is likewise thought to be regulated to some extent by AMPK activity.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] If the AMPK response to exercise is responsible in part for biochemical adaptations to training, how then can these adaptations to training be maintained if the AMPK response to exercise is being attenuated with training?
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] In other words, due to previous adaptations to training, AMPK will not be activated, and further adaptation will not occur, until the intracellular ATP levels become depleted from an even higher intensity energy challenge than prior to those previous adaptations.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Dietary antioxidants are vitamins A, C, and E, but the term has also been applied to various compounds that exhibit antioxidant properties in vitro, having little evidence for antioxidant properties in vivo.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Dietary supplements marketed as antioxidants have not been shown to maintain health or prevent disease in humans.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] As part of their adaptation from marine life, terrestrial plants began producing non-marine antioxidants such as ascorbic acid (vitamin C), polyphenols, and tocopherols.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The evolution of angiosperm plants between 50 and 200 million years ago resulted in the development of many antioxidant pigments – particularly during the Jurassic period – as chemical defences against reactive oxygen species that are byproducts of photosynthesis.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Originally, the term antioxidant specifically referred to a chemical that prevented the consumption of oxygen.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, extensive study concentrated on the use of antioxidants in important industrial processes, such as the prevention of metal corrosion, the vulcanization of rubber, and the polymerization of fuels in the fouling of internal combustion engines.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Early research on the role of antioxidants in biology focused on their use in preventing the oxidation of unsaturated fats, which is the cause of rancidity.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Antioxidant activity could be measured simply by placing the fat in a closed container with oxygen and measuring the rate of oxygen consumption.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] However, it was the identification of vitamins C and E as antioxidants that revolutionized the field and led to the realization of the importance of antioxidants in the biochemistry of living organisms.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The possible mechanisms of action of antioxidants were first explored when it was recognized that a substance with anti-oxidative activity is likely to be one that is itself readily oxidized.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Research into how vitamin E prevents the process of lipid peroxidation led to the identification of antioxidants as reducing agents that prevent oxidative reactions, often by scavenging reactive oxygen species before they can damage cells.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Antioxidants are added to food to prevent deterioration.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Exposure to oxygen and sunlight are the two main factors in the oxidation of food, so food is preserved by keeping in the dark and sealing it in containers or even coating it in wax, as with cucumbers.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] However, as oxygen is also important for plant respiration, storing plant materials in anaerobic conditions produces unpleasant flavors and unappealing colors.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Consequently, packaging of fresh fruits and vegetables contains an ≈8% oxygen atmosphere.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Antioxidants are an especially important class of preservatives as, unlike bacterial or fungal spoilage, oxidation reactions still occur relatively rapidly in frozen or refrigerated food.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] These preservatives include natural antioxidants such as ascorbic acid (AA, E300) and tocopherols (E306), as well as synthetic antioxidants such as propyl gallate (PG, E310), tertiary butylhydroquinone (TBHQ), butylated hydroxyanisole (BHA, E320) and butylated hydroxytoluene (BHT, E321).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Unsaturated fats can be highly susceptible to oxidation, causing rancidification.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Oxidized lipids are often discolored and can impart unpleasant tastes and flavors.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Thus, these foods are rarely preserved by drying; instead, they are preserved by smoking, salting, or fermenting.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Even less fatty foods such as fruits are sprayed with sulfurous antioxidants prior to air drying.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Some fatty foods such as olive oil are partially protected from oxidation by their natural content of antioxidants.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Fatty foods are sensitive to photooxidation, which forms hydroperoxides by oxidizing unsaturated fatty acids and ester.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation can cause direct photooxidation and decompose peroxides and carbonyl molecules.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] These molecules undergo free radical chain reactions, but antioxidants inhibit them by preventing the oxidation processes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Some pharmaceutical products require protection from oxidation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] A number of antioxidants can be used as excipients.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Sequestrants such as disodium EDTA can also be used to prevent metal-catalyzed oxidation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Antioxidant stabilizers are also added to fat-based cosmetics such as lipstick and moisturizers to prevent rancidity.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Antioxidants in cosmetic products prevent oxidation of active ingredients and lipid content.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] For example, phenolic antioxidants such as stilbenes, flavonoids, and hydroxycinnamic acid strongly absorb UV radiation due to the presence of chromophores.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] They reduce oxidative stress from sun exposure by absorbing UV light.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Antioxidants may be added to industrial products, such as stabilizers in fuels and additives in lubricants, to prevent oxidation and polymerization that leads to the formation of engine-fouling residues.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Antioxidant polymer stabilizers are widely used to prevent the degradation of polymers, such as rubbers, plastics and adhesives, that causes a loss of strength and flexibility in these materials.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Polymers containing double bonds in their main chains, such as natural rubber and polybutadiene, are especially susceptible to oxidation and ozonolysis.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Oxidation can be accelerated by UV radiation in natural sunlight to cause photo-oxidation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Various specialised light stabilisers, such as HALS may be added to plastics to prevent this.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Probucol was originally designed as an antioxidant polymer stabilizer for rubber tires.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] It was later found to reduce LDL-C levels independently of the LDL receptor and became a prescription drug.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Its approval predated statins by a decade.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Synthetic phenolic antioxidants (SPAs) and aminic antioxidants have potential human and environmental health hazards.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] SPAs are common in indoor dust, small air particles, sediment, sewage, river water and wastewater.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] They are synthesized from phenolic compounds and include 2,6-di-tert-butyl-4-methylphenol (BHT), 2,6-di-tert-butyl-p-benzoquinone (BHT-Q), 2,4-di-tert-butyl-phenol (DBP) and 3-*tert*-butyl-4-hydroxyanisole (BHA).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] BHT can cause hepatotoxicity and damage to the endocrine system and may increase the carcinogenicity of 1,1-dimethylhydrazine exposure.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] BHT-Q can cause DNA damage and mismatches through the cleavage process, generating superoxide radicals.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] DBP is toxic to marine life if exposed long-term.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Phenolic antioxidants have low biodegradability, but they do not have severe toxicity toward aquatic organisms at low concentrations.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Another type of antioxidant, diphenylamine (DPA), is commonly used in the production of commercial, industrial lubricants and rubber products and it also acts as a supplement for automotive engine oils.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The vast majority of complex life on Earth requires oxygen for its metabolism, but this same oxygen is a highly reactive element that can damage living organisms.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Organisms contain chemicals and enzymes that minimize this oxidative damage without interfering with the beneficial effect of oxygen.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] In general, antioxidant systems either prevent these reactive species from being formed, or remove them, thus minimizing their damage.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Reactive oxygen species can have useful cellular functions, such as redox signaling.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Thus, ideally, antioxidant systems do not remove oxidants entirely, but maintain them at some optimum concentration.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Reactive oxygen species produced in cells include hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), hypochlorous acid (HClO), and free radicals such as the hydroxyl radical (·OH), and the superoxide anion (O2−).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The hydroxyl radical is particularly unstable and will react rapidly and non-specifically with most biological molecules.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] This species is produced from hydrogen peroxide in metal-catalyzed redox reactions such as the Fenton reaction.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] These oxidants can damage cells by starting chemical chain reactions such as lipid peroxidation, or by oxidizing DNA or proteins.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Damage to DNA can cause mutations and possibly cancer, if not reversed by DNA repair mechanisms, while damage to proteins causes enzyme inhibition, denaturation, and protein degradation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The use of oxygen as part of the process for generating metabolic energy produces reactive oxygen species.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] In this process, the superoxide anion is produced as a by-product of several steps in the electron transport chain.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Particularly important is the reduction of coenzyme Q in complex III, since a highly reactive free radical is formed as an intermediate (Q**·**−).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] This unstable intermediate can lead to electron "leakage", when electrons jump directly to oxygen and form the superoxide anion, instead of moving through the normal series of well-controlled reactions of the electron transport chain.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Peroxide is also produced from the oxidation of reduced flavoproteins, such as complex I.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] However, although these enzymes can produce oxidants, the relative importance of the electron transfer chain to other processes that generate peroxide is unclear.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] In plants, algae, and cyanobacteria, reactive oxygen species are also produced during photosynthesis, particularly under conditions of high light intensity.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Physiological antioxidants are classified into two broad divisions, depending on whether they are soluble in water (hydrophilic) or in lipids (lipophilic).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] In general, water-soluble antioxidants react with oxidants in the cell cytosol and the blood plasma, while lipid-soluble antioxidants protect cell membranes from lipid peroxidation.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] These compounds may be synthesized in the body or obtained from the diet.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The different antioxidants are present at a wide range of concentrations in body fluids and tissues, with some such as glutathione or ubiquinone mostly present within cells, while others such as uric acid are more systemically distributed (see table below).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Some antioxidants are only found in a few organisms, and can be pathogens or virulence factors.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The interactions between these different antioxidants may be synergistic and interdependent.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The action of one antioxidant may therefore depend on the proper function of other members of the antioxidant system.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The amount of protection provided by any one antioxidant will also depend on its concentration, its reactivity towards the particular reactive oxygen species being considered, and the status of the antioxidants with which it interacts.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Some compounds contribute to antioxidant defense by chelating transition metals and preventing them from catalyzing the production of free radicals in the cell.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The ability to sequester iron for iron-binding proteins, such as transferrin and ferritin, is one such function.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Selenium and zinc are commonly referred to as *antioxidant minerals*, but these chemical elements have no antioxidant action themselves, but rather are required for the activity of antioxidant enzymes, such as glutathione reductase and superoxide dismutase.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Uric acid has the highest concentration of any blood antioxidant and provides over half of the total antioxidant capacity of human serum.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Uric acid's antioxidant activities are also complex, given that it does not react with some oxidants, such as superoxide, but does act against peroxynitrite, peroxides, and hypochlorous acid.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Concerns over elevated UA's contribution to gout must be considered one of many risk factors.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] By itself, UA-related risk of gout at high levels (415–530 μmol/L) is only 0.5% per year with an increase to 4.5% per year at UA supersaturation levels (535+ μmol/L).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Many of these aforementioned studies determined UA's antioxidant actions within normal physiological levels, and some found antioxidant activity at levels as high as 285 μmol/L.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Ascorbic acid or vitamin C, an oxidation-reduction (redox) catalyst found in both animals and plants, can reduce, and thereby neutralize, reactive oxygen species, such as hydrogen peroxide.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] In addition to its direct antioxidant effects, ascorbic acid is also a substrate for the redox enzyme ascorbate peroxidase, a function that is used in stress resistance in plants.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Ascorbic acid is present at high levels in all parts of plants and can reach concentrations of 20 millimolar in chloroplasts.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Glutathione has antioxidant properties since the thiol group in its cysteine moiety is a reducing agent and can be reversibly oxidized and reduced.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] In cells, glutathione is maintained in the reduced form by the enzyme glutathione reductase and in turn reduces other metabolites and enzyme systems, such as ascorbate in the glutathione-ascorbate cycle, glutathione peroxidases and glutaredoxins, as well as reacting directly with oxidants.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Due to its high concentration and its central role in maintaining the cell's redox state, glutathione is one of the most important cellular antioxidants.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] In some organisms glutathione is replaced by other thiols, such as by mycothiol in the Actinomycetes, bacillithiol in some gram-positive bacteria, or by trypanothione in the Kinetoplastids.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] A derivative of glutathione, glutathione hydropersulfide, operates as an abundant radical-trapping antioxidant with greater potency against free radical oxidation than glutathione itself.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Vitamin E is the collective name for a set of eight related tocopherols and tocotrienols, which are fat-soluble vitamins with antioxidant properties.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Of these, α-tocopherol has been most studied as it has the highest bioavailability, with the body preferentially absorbing and metabolising this form.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Alpha-tocopherol is the lipid-soluble antioxidant that protects membranes from oxidation by reacting with lipid radicals produced in the lipid peroxidation chain reaction.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] This removes the free radical intermediates and prevents the propagation reaction from continuing.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] This reaction produces oxidized α-tocopheroxyl radicals that can be recycled back to the active reduced form by other antioxidants, such as ascorbate.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The functions of the other forms of vitamin E are less well understood, although γ-tocopherol is a nucleophile that may react with electrophilic mutagens, and tocotrienols may be important in protecting neurons from damage.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Antioxidants that are reducing agents can also act as pro-oxidants.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] For example, vitamin C has antioxidant activity when it reduces oxidizing substances such as hydrogen peroxide; however, it will also reduce metal ions such as iron and copper that generate free radicals through the Fenton reaction.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] While ascorbic acid is effective antioxidant, it can also oxidatively change the flavor and color of food.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] With the presence of transition metals, there are low concentrations of ascorbic acid that can act as a radical scavenger in the Fenton reaction.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The relative importance of the antioxidant and pro-oxidant activities of antioxidants is an area of current research, but vitamin C, which exerts its effects as a vitamin by oxidizing polypeptides, appears to have a mostly antioxidant action in the human body.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] As with the chemical antioxidants, cells are protected against oxidative stress by an interacting network of antioxidant enzymes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Here, the superoxide released by processes such as oxidative phosphorylation is first converted to hydrogen peroxide and then further reduced to give water.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] This detoxification pathway is the result of multiple enzymes, with superoxide dismutases catalysing the first step and then catalases and various peroxidases removing hydrogen peroxide.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] As with antioxidant metabolites, the contributions of these enzymes to antioxidant defenses can be hard to separate from one another, but the generation of transgenic mice lacking just one antioxidant enzyme can be informative.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Superoxide dismutases (SODs) are a class of closely related enzymes that catalyze the breakdown of the superoxide anion into oxygen and hydrogen peroxide.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] SOD enzymes are present in almost all aerobic cells and in extracellular fluids.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Superoxide dismutase enzymes contain metal ion cofactors that, depending on the isozyme, can be copper, zinc, manganese or iron.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] In humans, the copper/zinc SOD is present in the cytosol, while manganese SOD is present in the mitochondrion.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] There also exists a third form of SOD in extracellular fluids, which contains copper and zinc in its active sites.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The mitochondrial isozyme seems to be the most biologically important of these three, since mice lacking this enzyme die soon after birth.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] In contrast, the mice lacking copper/zinc SOD (Sod1) are viable but have numerous pathologies and a reduced lifespan (see article on superoxide), while mice without the extracellular SOD have minimal defects (sensitive to hyperoxia).
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] In plants, SOD isozymes are present in the cytosol and mitochondria, with an iron SOD found in chloroplasts that is absent from vertebrates and yeast.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Catalases are enzymes that catalyse the conversion of hydrogen peroxide to water and oxygen, using either an iron or manganese cofactor.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] This protein is localized to peroxisomes in most eukaryotic cells.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Catalase is an unusual enzyme since, although hydrogen peroxide is its only substrate, it follows a ping-pong mechanism.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Here, its cofactor is oxidised by one molecule of hydrogen peroxide and then regenerated by transferring the bound oxygen to a second molecule of substrate.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Despite its apparent importance in hydrogen peroxide removal, humans with genetic deficiency of catalase — "acatalasemia" — or mice genetically engineered to lack catalase completely, experience few ill effects.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Peroxiredoxins are peroxidases that catalyze the reduction of hydrogen peroxide, organic hydroperoxides, as well as peroxynitrite.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] They are divided into three classes: typical 2-cysteine peroxiredoxins; atypical 2-cysteine peroxiredoxins; and 1-cysteine peroxiredoxins.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] These enzymes share the same basic catalytic mechanism, in which a redox-active cysteine (the peroxidatic cysteine) in the active site is oxidized to a sulfenic acid by the peroxide substrate.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Over-oxidation of this cysteine residue in peroxiredoxins inactivates these enzymes, but this can be reversed by the action of sulfiredoxin.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Peroxiredoxins seem to be important in antioxidant metabolism, as mice lacking peroxiredoxin 1 or 2 have shortened lifespans and develop hemolytic anaemia, while plants use peroxiredoxins to remove hydrogen peroxide generated in chloroplasts.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The thioredoxin system contains the 12 kDa protein thioredoxin and its companion thioredoxin reductase.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Proteins related to thioredoxin are present in all sequenced organisms.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Plants, such as *Arabidopsis thaliana,* have a particularly great diversity of isoforms.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The active site of thioredoxin consists of two neighboring cysteines, as part of a highly conserved CXXC motif, that can cycle between an active dithiol form (reduced) and an oxidized disulfide form.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] In its active state, thioredoxin acts as an efficient reducing agent, scavenging reactive oxygen species and maintaining other proteins in their reduced state.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] After being oxidized, the active thioredoxin is regenerated by the action of thioredoxin reductase, using NADPH as an electron donor.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The glutathione system includes glutathione, glutathione reductase, glutathione peroxidases, and glutathione *S*-transferases.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] This system is found in animals, plants and microorganisms.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Glutathione peroxidase is an enzyme containing four selenium-cofactors that catalyzes the breakdown of hydrogen peroxide and organic hydroperoxides.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] There are at least four different glutathione peroxidase isozymes in animals.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Glutathione peroxidase 1 is the most abundant and is a very efficient scavenger of hydrogen peroxide, while glutathione peroxidase 4 is most active with lipid hydroperoxides.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Surprisingly, glutathione peroxidase 1 is dispensable, as mice lacking this enzyme have normal lifespans, but they are hypersensitive to induced oxidative stress.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] In addition, the glutathione *S*-transferases show high activity with lipid peroxides.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] These enzymes are at particularly high levels in the liver and also serve in detoxification metabolism.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The dietary antioxidant vitamins A, C, and E are essential and required in specific daily amounts to prevent diseases.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Polyphenols, which have antioxidant properties in vitro due to their free hydroxy groups, are extensively metabolized by catechol-O-methyltransferase which methylates free hydroxyl groups, and thereby prevents them from acting as antioxidants in vivo.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Common pharmaceuticals (and supplements) with antioxidant properties may interfere with the efficacy of certain anticancer medications and radiation therapy.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Pharmaceuticals and supplements that have antioxidant properties suppress the formation of free radicals by inhibiting oxidation processes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Radiation therapy induces oxidative stress that damages essential components of cancer cells, such as proteins, nucleic acids, and lipids that comprise cell membranes.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Relatively strong reducing acids can have antinutrient effects by binding to dietary minerals such as iron and zinc in the gastrointestinal tract and preventing them from being absorbed.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Examples are oxalic acid, tannins and phytic acid, which are high in plant-based diets.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Calcium and iron deficiencies are not uncommon in diets in developing countries where less meat is eaten and there is high consumption of phytic acid from beans and unleavened whole grain bread.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] However, germination, soaking, or microbial fermentation are all household strategies that reduce the phytate and polyphenol content of unrefined cereal.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Increases in Fe, Zn and Ca absorption have been reported in adults fed dephytinized cereals compared with cereals containing their native phytate.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] High doses of some antioxidants may have harmful long-term effects.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The *Beta-Carotene and Retinol Efficacy Trial* (CARET) study of lung cancer patients found that smokers given supplements containing beta-carotene and vitamin A had increased rates of lung cancer.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] These harmful effects may also be seen in non-smokers, as one meta-analysis including data from approximately 230,000 patients showed that β-carotene, vitamin A or vitamin E supplementation is associated with increased mortality, but saw no significant effect from vitamin C.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] No health risk was seen when all the randomized controlled studies were examined together, but an increase in mortality was detected when only high-quality and low-bias risk trials were examined separately.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] As the majority of these low-bias trials dealt with either elderly people, smokers, or people with disease, these results may not apply to the general population.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] This meta-analysis was later repeated and extended by the same authors, confirming the previous results.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] These two publications are consistent with some previous meta-analyses that also suggested that vitamin E supplementation increased mortality, and that antioxidant supplements increased the risk of colon cancer.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] In the Selenium and Vitamin E Cancer Prevention Trial (SELECT study), vitamin E – alone or combined with selenium – had no effect on the risk of prostate cancer.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Beta-carotene may also increase lung cancer.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Overall, the large number of clinical trials carried out on antioxidant supplements suggest that either these products have no effect on health, or that they cause a small increase in mortality in elderly or vulnerable populations.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] A 2017 review showed that taking antioxidant dietary supplements before or after exercise is unlikely to produce a noticeable reduction in muscle soreness after a person exercises.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Antioxidant vitamins are found in vegetables, fruits, eggs, legumes and nuts.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Vitamins A, C, and E can be destroyed by long-term storage or prolonged cooking.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] The effects of cooking and food processing are complex, as these processes can also increase the bioavailability of antioxidants, such as some carotenoids in vegetables.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Processed food contains fewer antioxidant vitamins than fresh and uncooked foods, as preparation exposes food to heat and oxygen.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Other antioxidants are not obtained from the diet, but instead are made in the body.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] For example, ubiquinol (coenzyme Q) is poorly absorbed from the gut and is made through the mevalonate pathway.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Another example is glutathione, which is made from amino acids.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] As any glutathione in the gut is broken down to free cysteine, glycine and glutamic acid before being absorbed, even large oral intake has little effect on the concentration of glutathione in the body.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Although large amounts of sulfur-containing amino acids such as acetylcysteine can increase glutathione, no evidence exists that eating high levels of these glutathione precursors is beneficial for healthy adults.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Measurement of polyphenol and carotenoid content in food is not a straightforward process, as antioxidants collectively are a diverse group of compounds with different reactivities to various reactive oxygen species.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] In food science analyses in vitro, the oxygen radical absorbance capacity (ORAC) was once an industry standard for estimating antioxidant strength of whole foods, juices and food additives, mainly from the presence of polyphenols.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Earlier measurements and ratings by the United States Department of Agriculture were withdrawn in 2012 as biologically irrelevant to human health, referring to an absence of physiological evidence for polyphenols having antioxidant properties *in vivo*.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Consequently, the ORAC method, derived only from *in vitro* experiments, is no longer considered relevant to human diets or biology, as of 2010.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/antioxidant] Alternative in vitro measurements of antioxidant content in foods – also based on the presence of polyphenols – include the Folin-Ciocalteu reagent, and the Trolox equivalent antioxidant capacity assay.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/asymptomatic] An example of an asymptomatic disease is cytomegalovirus (CMV) which is a member of the herpes virus family.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/asymptomatic] "It is estimated that 1% of all newborns are infected with CMV, but the majority of infections are asymptomatic." (Knox, 1983; Kumar et al.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/asymptomatic] 1984) In some diseases, the proportion of asymptomatic cases can be important.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/asymptomatic] For example, in multiple sclerosis it is estimated that around 25% of the cases are asymptomatic, with these cases detected postmortem or just by coincidence (as incidental findings) while treating other diseases.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/asymptomatic] Subclinical or subthreshold conditions are those for which the full diagnostic criteria are not met and have not been met in the past, although symptoms are present.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/asymptomatic] This can mean that symptoms are not severe enough to merit a diagnosis, or that symptoms are severe but do not meet the criteria of a condition.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/asymptomatic] These are conditions for which there is a sufficient number of documented individuals that are asymptomatic that it is clinically noted.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/asymptomatic] For a complete list of asymptomatic infections see subclinical infection.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/asymptomatic] Millions of women reported lack of symptoms during pregnancy until the point of childbirth or the beginning of labor and did not know they were pregnant.
[src:6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency/asymptomatic] This phenomenon is known as cryptic pregnancies.
